ing's confessors and corrodies of the crown provide insights into the intersection of political, religious and demographic currents over the longue durée, and are complemented by studies of documentary sources of various kinds - newsletters, chronicles, and municipal archives - to challenge current understandings of important events and processes such as the deposition of Edward II, the evolving identity of the parliamentary peers, and Richard II's vision for the house of Lancaster. Prosopographical and biographical studies of post-plague clerics, and of knights within comital affinities and within their own individual affinity groups, shed light on county communities and gentry society; they also demonstrate the impact of the Black Death on society at large, especially on the question of religious continuity and discontinuity at the parish level. Contributors: Paul Dryburgh, Pierre Gaite, Chris Given-Wilson, Michael Jones, Taylor Kniphfer, Samuel Lane, Jonathan Mackman, Alison McHardy, Matt Raven, David Robinson.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGreat BritainxHistoryy14th century. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Norman Conquest to Late Medieval (1066-1485).2bisacsh  aBlack Death.  achurch.  adisposition.  agentry.  amonarchy.  anobility.  aparliament.  apolitics.  awar.1 aBothwell, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDryburgh, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaite, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiven-Wilson, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiven-Wilson, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJ.S. Hamilton, Jeffrey S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela